******
[1] Undiagnosed rust, wheat - France (Normandy), request for information
Date: Sat 2 May 2009
From: Susan Baekeland <grolleyog@wanadoo.fr>


We have an outbreak of some sort of common rust in winter wheat. I do
not know which, nor does anyone else farming here.

On examination of the crop I saw that the tips of the leaves were
brown/beige, and there were yellow/orange spots on the rib of the
leaves. The farmer confirmed the rust. He did not know what the type
was but said he had sprayed this crop 14 days ago and it would have
to be re-done.

I showed samples to another farmer and he said yes that it was the
rust (type not specified), it is this wet and warm weather we have
been having, which is ideal for the growth of this fungus.

Looking at more wheat fields in the area, about 85 percent were
infected with this rust. In some fields it is just starting, in
others it is quite well established. It is the most common one. No
stripes.

It is a problem because at the moment farmers are spraying herbicide
on fields to prepare to plant maize, and now they have to treat the
wheat with a fungicide as well.

--
Susan Baekeland
ProMED-mail Rapporteur
Veterinarian
La Meute du Ruisseau
Le Ruisseau
50240, Carnet
St James, Normandy
France
<grolleyog@wanadoo.fr>

